onal Rugby League]] and [[NRL Women's Premiership]]\n  | season                 = [[2019 NRL season|2019 season]]\n  | position               = '''Premiers (NRL)'''<br/>4th (NRLW)\n  | premierships           = 15\n  | premiershipyears       = [[1911 NSWRFL season|1911]], [[1912 NSWRFL season|1912]], [[1913 NSWRFL season|1913]], [[1923 NSWRFL season|1923]], [[1935 NSWRFL season|1935]], [[1936 NSWRFL season|1936]], [[1937 NSWRFL season|1937]], [[1940 NSWRFL season|1940]], [[1945 NSWRFL season|1945]], [[1974 NSWRFL season|1974]], [[1975 NSWRFL season|1975]], [[2002 NRL season|2002]], [[2013 NRL season|2013]], [[2018 NRL season|2018]], [[2019 NRL season|2019]]\n  | runnerups              = 15\n  | runnerupyears          = [[1908 NSWRFL season|1908]], [[1919 NSWRFL season|1919]], [[1921 NSWRFL season|1921]], [[1928 NSWRFL season|1928]], [[1931 NSWRFL season|1931]], [[1934 NSWRFL season|1934]], [[1938 NSWRFL season|1938]], [[1941 NSWRFL season|1941]], [[1960 NSWRFL season|1960]], [[1972 NSWRFL season|1972]], [[1980 NSWRFL season|1980]], [[2000 NRL season|2000]], [[2003 NRL season|2003]], [[2004 NRL season|2004]], [[2010 NRL season|2010]]\n  | minorpremierships      = 20\n  | minorpremiershipyears  = [[1912 NSWRFL season|1912]], [[1913 NSWRFL season|1913]], [[1923 NSWRFL season|1923]], [[1931 NSWRFL season|1931]], [[1934 NSWRFL season|1934]], [[1935 NSWRFL season|1935]], [[1936 NSWRFL season|1936]], [[1937 NSWRFL season|1937]], [[1940 NSWRFL season|1940]], [[1941 NSWRFL season|1941]], [[1945 NSWRFL season|1945]], [[1974 NSWRFL season|1974]], [[1975 NSWRFL season|1975]], [[1980 NSWRFL season|1980]], [[1981 NSWRFL season|1981]], [[2004 NRL season|2004]], [[2013 NRL season|2013]], [[2014 NRL season|2014]], [[2015 NRL season|2015]], [[2018 NRL season|2018]]\n  | spoons                 = 5\n  | spoonyears             = [[1949 NSWRFL season|1949]], [[1963 NSWRFL season|1963]], [[1965 NSWRFL season|1965]], [[1966 NSWRFL season|1966]], [[2009 NRL season|2009]]\n | cap                    = 302\n  | mostcap                = [[Anthony Minichiello]]\n  | points                 = 1,376\n  | mostpoints             = [[Craig Fitzgibbon]]\n  | current                = 2019 Sydney Roosters season\n  | homejersey             = \n  | awayjersey             = \n| pattern_la1        = _Easts2017\n| pattern_b1         = _Easts2017\n| pattern_ra1        = _Easts2017\n| pattern_sh1        = \n| pattern_so1        = _hoops_blue_red\n| leftarm1           = 000080\n| body1              = 000080\n| rightarm1          = 000080\n| shorts1            = FFFFFF\n| socks1             = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la2        = _EastsA2017\n| pattern_b2         = _EastsA2017\n| pattern_ra2        = _EastsA2017\n| pattern_sh2        = \n| pattern_so2        = _hoops_blue_red\n| leftarm2           = 000080\n| body2              = 000080\n| rightarm2          = 000080\n| shorts2            = 000080\n| socks2             = FFFFFF\n  |cup1                    = [[World Club Challenge]]\n  | cup1titles            = 5\n  |cup1years               = [[1976 World Club Challenge|1976]], [[2003 World Club Challenge|2003]], [[2014 World Club Challenge|2014]], [[2019 World Club Challenge|2019]], [[2020 World Club Challenge|2020]]\n  |cup2                   = [[NRL Nines]]\n  | cup2titles            = 1\n  |cup2years              = 2017\n}}\n\nThe '''Sydney Roosters''' is an Australian professional [[rugby league]] football club based in the [[Eastern Suburbs (Sydney)|Eastern Suburbs of Sydney]]. The club competes in the [[National Rugby League]] (NRL) competition and is one of the oldest and most successful clubs. The Roosters have won fifteen [[New South Wales Rugby League premiership|New South Wales Rugby League]] (NSWRL) and National Rugby League titles, and several other competitions. As a franchise, the Eastern Suburbs/Sydney City/Sydney Roosters have won 15 premierships, tying them with the St George Dragons. Only [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]] have won more premierships. The club holds the record for having the most wins and the second greatest margin of victory in a match in Australian rugby league history, and has won more minor premierships than any other club. The Roosters is one of only two clubs (the other being the [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]] in 1999) to finish runners-up in its inaugural season. The Eastern Suburbs DRLFC is the only club to have played in each and every season at the elite level, and since the 1970s has often been dubbed the \"glamour club\" of the league.<ref>{{cite news|first=Josh|last=Rakic|title=There's still reason to hate those Roosters: Champion|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/theres-still-reason-to-hate-those-roosters-champion-20100313-q55o.html|newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=14 March 2010|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> Coached by [[Trent Robinson]] along with captains [[Boyd Cordner]] and [[Jake Friend]], the Roosters play their home games at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].\n\nThe club was founded in 1908 in [[Paddington, New South Wales|Paddington]], Sydney, as Eastern Suburbs District Rugby League Football Club; in 1995 the club's name was changed to the Sydney City Roosters, and in 2000 to the Sydney Roosters. The [[Bondi Junction, New South Wales|Bondi Junction]] and [[Moore Park, New South Wales|Moore Park]]-based Roosters have a long-standing and fierce rivalry with other Sydney-based clubs, especially the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]], a fellow foundation club based in neighbouring [[Redfern, New South Wales|Redfern]].<ref>In Australia, a foundation club is one that played in the first season of a competition. Eastern Suburbs played in the first season of the New South Wales Rugby League premiership in 1908, the predecessor to the National Rugby League competition. Notwithstanding its branding as the Sydney Roosters, the official name of the club, holder of the NRL licence, remains the Eastern Suburbs District Rugby League Football Club, the same licensee since 1908. As such, much of the club's merchandise and paraphernalia, especially those marketed directly to long-serving and dedicated members, includes the insignia ESDRLFC.</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of the Sydney Roosters}}\nThe Eastern Suburbs District Rugby League Football Club (ESDRLFC) was formed on 24 January 1908<ref name=\"rl1908\" /> at a meeting at the Paddington Town Hall in Sydney<ref name=cw16>Collis and Whiticker, p. 16.</ref> after it was decided that the district should enter a team in the newly formed [[New South Wales Rugby Football League]].<ref name=cw12>Collis and Whiticker, p. 12.</ref> The ESDRLFC was formed, under its articles of association with the NSWRL, to represent the geographic areas in Sydney covering the Waverley, Randwick, Woollahra, Paddington, Darlinghurst and Vaucluse local government municipalities, as well as the eastern parts of the Sydney CBD. Indeed, the 'suburb' of Sydney, postcode 2000, falls entirely within the official boundaries of the ESDRLFC.\n\nUnofficially nicknamed the \"Tricolours\" due to their red, white and blue playing strip,<ref name=cw29>Collis and Whiticker, p. 29.</ref> Eastern Suburbs won its [[Eastern Suburbs season 1908|first match]], defeating [[Newtown Jets|Newtown]] 32\u201316 at [[Wentworth Park|Wentworth Oval]] on 20 April 1908.<ref name=cw16/> In 1913, it became the first club to win three consecutive [[New South Wales Rugby League premiership|premierships]];<ref name=\"rl1908\" /><ref name=\"history1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/yourroosters/roosters1908to2005.php  |title=Club History: Sydney Roosters Rugby League 2006 |accessdate=8 October 2006 |publisher=Sydney Roosters |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070204080841/http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/yourroosters/roosters1908to2005.php |archivedate = 4 February 2007}}</ref><ref name=cw381>Collis and Whiticker, p. 381.</ref> the line-ups during this period included the likes of [[Dally Messenger]], [[Jersey Flegg|Harry \"Jersey\" Flegg]] and [[Sandy Pearce]], all regarded as all-time rugby league greats.<ref name=\"rl1908\"/><ref>Collis and Whiticker, pp. 16\u201317.</ref> However, the club rapidly declined and failed to win the premiership for the next nine seasons.<ref name=cw381/>\n\nEastern Suburbs missed the finals once from 1926 to 1942, and in that time won four titles and the [[minor premiership]] on seven occasions.<ref name=cw29/><ref name=\"season\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/easts/easts_ss.html |title=Rugby League Tables / Season Summary / Easts |publisher=Rugby League Tables & Statistics |access-date=13 August 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705001049/http://www.stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/easts/easts_ss.html |archive-date=5 July 2009  }}</ref> During this period, [[Dave Brown (rugby league, born 1913)|Dave Brown]] set several point-scoring records that still stand.<ref name=cw20>Collis and Whiticker, p. 20.</ref> In [[New South Wales Rugby Football League season 1935|1935]], the team lost just one game,<ref name=cw21>Collis and Whiticker, p. 21.</ref> and recorded the highest winning margin in their history, an 87\u20137 (106\u20138 in modern scoring) victory over [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Canterbury]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/easts/easts_gr.html |title=Rugby League Tables / Regular Season / All Teams |publisher=Rugby League Tables & Statistics |access-date=6 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060830192722/http://stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/easts/easts_gr.html |archive-date=30 August 2006  }}</ref> In [[New South Wales Rugby Football League season 1936|1936]], Eastern Suburbs became one of five teams in premiership history to remain undefeated for an entire season,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/all/overall_sr.html |title=Rugby League Tables / Game Records / Easts |publisher=Rugby League Tables & Statistics |access-date=6 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060829204850/http://stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/all/overall_sr.html |archive-date=29 August 2006  }}</ref> a feat they repeated the following year.<ref name=cw21/> They are the only club to remain unbeaten for two consecutive seasons.<ref name=Sum/>\n\n[[File:Dan Frawley in action.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Easts pioneers [[Dan Frawley]] (right) and [[Dally Messenger]] (left) in action for NSW in 1912.]]\n\nDespite claiming the [[New South Wales Rugby League premiership|premiership]] in 1945, Eastern Suburbs failed to make the finals for the following seven seasons.<ref>Collis and Whiticker, pp. 22\u201323.</ref> A [[runner-up|runners-up]] finish in 1960 was the closest the club came to claiming the premiership during this era.<ref name=cw29/> Eastern Suburbs were soundly defeated 31\u20136 in the [[New South Wales Rugby League season 1960#Grand Final|grand final that year]], by the famous record-beating St George outfit.<ref>Collis and Whiticker, pp. 24\u201325.</ref> In 1966, the club fell to new depths and was winless for the first time in its history.<ref name=cw23>Collis and Whiticker, p. 23.</ref><ref name=am658>Andrews, p. 658.</ref> It was also the last occasion in which the Roosters won the [[wooden spoon (award)|wooden spoon]] until claiming it again in the 2009 season.<ref name=Sum>{{cite web|url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/easts/easts_ss.html |title=Rugby League Tables / Season Summary / Sydney Roosters |access-date=14 April 2009 |publisher=Rleague |author=Jeffs, Paul |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419173550/http://stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/easts/easts_ss.html |archive-date=19 April 2009 |df= }}</ref> It ended a poor run for Eastern Suburbs; from 1963 to 1966, they won 8 of 72 matches, finishing second to last in 1964 and last in the other three years.<ref name=cw24>Collis and Whiticker, p. 24.</ref> The club underwent a renaissance in 1967 after appointing [[Jack Gibson (rugby league)|Jack Gibson]] as coach (1967\u201368), and introducing a new emblem on the playing jerseys, the [[rooster]].<ref name=cw24/>\n\nFrom 1972 to 1982, the Roosters won four [[minor premiership]]s and played in four grand finals,<ref name=cw29/> winning two consecutively.<ref name=cw29/> Gibson, now dubbed as \"Super Coach\",<ref>Collis and Whiticker, pp. 24\u201326.</ref> returned to lead the team from 1974 to 1976.<ref>The titling of Gibson as \"Super Coach\" is common terminology in Australian rugby league references, given his outstanding coaching record. See {{cite web| url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/08/14/1060588510800.html?from=storyrhs |title=Super coach Gibson salutes his favourite players |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=14 August 2003 |accessdate=8 October 2006}}</ref><ref name=cw25>Collis and Whiticker, p. 25.</ref> In [[New South Wales Rugby Football League season 1974|1974]] and [[New South Wales Rugby Football League season 1975|1975]], the team won 39 of 44 matches,<ref name=cw25/> both minor premierships, and both grand finals and set a premiership record of 19 consecutive wins.<ref name=cw29/><ref name=cw25/> The 38\u20130 [[New South Wales Rugby Football League season 1975#Grand Final|grand final victory in 1975]] against St George was the largest margin in a first grade grand final,<ref name=cw26>Collis and Whiticker, p. 26.</ref> and the record stood for 33&nbsp;years until superseded by Manly's 40\u2013nil win over the [[Melbourne Storm]] in [[National Rugby League season 2008|2008]]. Though the 1975 grand final was played in the era of an obsolete scoring system with 3-point tries, the winning margin using 4 points for tries would mean that it is still a record for a grand final at 46\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Walter, Brad |author2=Pandaram, Jamie |work=[[Brisbane Times]] |title=Manly's five-year plan |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/articles/2008/10/05/1223145207693.html |access-date=13 April 2009 |date=6 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801060649/http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/articles/2008/10/05/1223145207693.html |archive-date=1 August 2015  }}</ref> With line-ups including [[Mark Harris (rugby league)|Mark Harris]], [[Elwyn Walters]], [[John Brass]], [[Bill Mullins]], [[Russell Fairfax]], [[Johnny Mayes]], [[John Peard]], [[Ron Coote]], [[Ian Schubert]] and captain [[Arthur Beetson]],<ref name = \"rl1908\"/><ref>Collis and Whiticker, pp. 25\u201326.</ref> the [[Centenary of Rugby League]] panel considered the Roosters of 1974 and 1975 to be among the greatest club teams of all time.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[National Rugby League]] |title=Team of the Century Announced |url=http://www.centenaryofrugbyleague.com.au/site/news--reviews/media-releases/team-of-the-century-announced.aspx |access-date=13 April 2009 |date=17 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100521122127/http://www.centenaryofrugbyleague.com.au/site/news--reviews/media-releases/team-of-the-century-announced.aspx |archive-date=21 May 2010  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Three Rooster Blues 1931.jpg|thumb|right|Three representative Roosters in 1931:\n[[Dave Brown (rugby league, born 1913)|Brown]], [[Ernie Norman|Norman]] and [[Ray Stehr|Stehr.]]]]\n\nBetween 1984 and 1995, the Roosters reached the semi-finals once,<ref name=Sum/> and became known to critics as the \"transit lounge\", due to the high frequency of player purchases and releases.<ref name=\"history1\" /><ref name=cw27>Collis and Whiticker, p. 27.</ref> The club came close to reaching the premiership in 1987 under coach and favourite son Arthur Beetson, being defeated by eventual premiers [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly]] in a \"bruising\" major semi-final, 10\u20136.<ref name=dm87>Middleton, p. 108.</ref>\n\nAs the [[Super League war]] built up in the mid-1990s, the Roosters recruited high-profile coach [[Phil Gould (rugby league)|Phil Gould]] and star five-eighth [[Brad Fittler]], both from the [[Penrith Panthers]].<ref name=\"rl1908\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rl1908.com/Clubs/Sydney-Roosters.htm |title=Sydney Roosters (Eastern Suburbs) |publisher=RL1908.com |access-date=15 August 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061021080326/http://www.rl1908.com/Clubs/Sydney-Roosters.htm |archive-date=21 October 2006  }}</ref><ref name=cw27/> This helped to quickly send the Roosters back to the upper end of the ladder. Fittler's presence proved invaluable;<ref name=cw27/> during his reign, the Roosters competed in four grand finals in five years.<ref name=cw29/> In 2002, the club captured its 12th premiership \u2013 the first in 27 years \u2013 defeating Minor Premiers the [[New Zealand Warriors]] 30\u20138 in the [[2002 NRL grand final]].<ref name=cw28>Collis and Whiticker, p. 28.</ref>\n\nIn the [[2003 NRL grand final]] against the [[Penrith Panthers]], the Roosters lost 18\u20136 in what was their heaviest defeat for the year. A decisive moment occurred midway through the second half: with the scores tied at 6-all, Roosters winger [[Todd Byrne]] made a clear break down the sideline and looked set to score a try before being chased down and tackled into touch by Penrith lock forward, [[Scott Sattler]]. From then on, the momentum of the game was with Penrith.<ref name=cw28/><ref>{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Alex |author2=Brown, Malcolm|author3=Maley, Jacqueline |url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/10/05/1065292479504.html?from=storyrhs |title=Fairytale of the year: Panthers pluck Roosters |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=6 October 2003 |accessdate=4 November 2006}}</ref> The Roosters' made the Grand Final in [[National Rugby League season 2004|2004]], when they ceded a 13\u20136 half-time lead to be defeated by the [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Bulldogs]] 16\u201313. The match was captain Fittler's last for the team.<ref name=sh330>Haddan, p. 330.</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the Roosters became the first club to play 100 seasons of first grade rugby league; they were the only outfit to play in each season since the competition's inception in 1908. They appointed [[Chris Anderson (rugby league)|Chris Anderson]] as coach in 2007 and 2008 following two relatively unsuccessful years under [[Ricky Stuart]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Walter |first= Brad |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/league/a-sticky-end-for-ricky/2006/08/28/1156617274414.html |title=A sticky end for Ricky |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=29 August 2006 |accessdate=4 November 2006}}</ref> On 9 July 2007, Anderson resigned after a 56\u20130 loss to the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Phil  |last=Rothfield|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|title=Anderson out, Freddy in |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,22047691-5001021,00.html |accessdate=13 April 2009|date=10 July 2007}}</ref> Assistant Coach Fittler acted as the caretaker for the remainder of the 2007 season, before being appointed in August to the top job for two years.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/08/21/2010664.htm?section=sport | title=Fittler made Roosters head coach | work=ABC | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation | date=21 August 2007 | accessdate=13 April 2009}}</ref> With eight rounds remaining in a disappointing 2009 season in which the Roosters finished with the [[wooden spoon (award)|wooden spoon]] for the first time in 43 years, Fittler was informed he would not be the coach in 2010, his position to be taken by veteran coach [[Brian Smith (rugby league, born 1954)|Brian Smith]]. The Roosters wound up winning only five games for the entire season; twice against [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks|Cronulla]] and once against each of [[Canberra Raiders|Canberra]] in Canberra, eventual grand finalists [[Parramatta Eels|Parramatta]] and [[Newcastle Knights|Newcastle]] in Newcastle.\n\nA year after finishing last, under the coaching of Brian Smith they reached the [[2010 NRL Grand Final]] where the [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]] defeated them 32\u20138. The Roosters led 8\u20136 at half time but were overrun in the second half.\n\nWhat followed was another relatively disappointing season at Bondi Junction, with the Roosters finishing 11th in a 2011 season plagued by off-field issues involving 2010 [[Dally M Medal]]list [[Todd Carney]] (who was later sacked by the Roosters at season's end). However, a four-game winning streak to end the season brought hope for the 2012 season. Other high-profile players including [[Nate Myles]], [[Mark Riddell]], [[Jason Ryles]], [[Kane Linnett]] and [[Phil Graham (rugby league)|Phil Graham]] all left the club at season's end.\n\nThe Roosters endured a disappointing [[2012 NRL season|2012 season]], finishing 13th. [[Brian Smith (rugby league, born 1954)|Brian Smith]] resigned from the coaching role shortly after the Roosters' season concluded with a loss to the Minor Premiers [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Canterbury]], and also at season's end captain Braith Anasta left to join the [[Wests Tigers]] in 2013.\n\nThe [[2013 Sydney Roosters season|2013 season]] saw new staff, a new coach, [[Trent Robinson]], and several new players, including big signings [[Michael Jennings (rugby league)|Michael Jennings]], [[James Maloney (rugby league)|James Maloney]], [[Luke O'Donnell]] and [[Sonny Bill Williams]], arrive at the club. This culminated in the Roosters finishing the 2013 season with a 24\u201312 win over the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]], securing the Minor Premiership for the 2013 season and were the NRL's best attacking and defensive team.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/sydney-roosters-need-to-lift-their-game-to-go-backtoback-say-grand-final-heroes-20140223-33ack.html?skin=text-only Sydney Roosters need to lift their game to go back-to-back, say grand final heroes], by Michael Chammas, ''The Age'', dated 23 February 2014.</ref> The Roosters defeated the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] 4\u20130, in week one of the finals, earning a week's rest. The Roosters defeated the [[Newcastle Knights]] 40\u201314 in week three of the NRL finals, progressing to the 2013 NRL grand final, facing the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]], winning 26\u201318. It was a great comeback by the Roosters, down by 10 points in the second half they went on to score three consecutive tries to seal the win and their 13th premiership. They then went on to win the [[2014 World Club Challenge]] against Wigan 36\u201314 to claim the treble of club titles. No team in premiership history had come from a lower ladder position to win the following season's title.<ref>[http://rugbyleagueopinions.com/ GREATEST 12-MONTH TURNAROUNDS IN AUSTRALIAN RUGBY LEAGUE], by Will Evans, Rugby League Opinions, dated 21 October 2014.</ref>\n\nIn the 2014 season, the club finished first on the table winning the Minor Premiership.  In the Preliminary Final against arch rivals Souths, Sydney lost the match 32\u201322 in what was retiring legend Anthony Minichiello's final game.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2014/09/30/sydney-roosters-season-review/</ref>\nIn the 2015 season, Sydney finished first on the table and claimed their third consecutive Minor Premiership.  The Roosters again made the Preliminary Final with Brisbane this time being the opponents.  The Roosters ended up losing the match 31\u201312 in front of a sold-out crowd at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2015/09/28/roosters-2015-season-review/</ref>\n\nIn the 2016 season, the Roosters finished 15th on the table after enduring a horror season where star player Mitchell Pearce was suspended for 8 matches, fined $125,000 and stripped of the captaincy following a pre season incident where the player who was intoxicated, simulated a sex act with a dog which was filmed on another party goer's mobile phone.  The club also struggled due to injuries to star players such as [[Boyd Cordner]] and [[Jared Waerea-Hargreaves]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/mar/03/mitchell-pearce-handed-eight-week-suspension-and-fined</ref><ref>https://www.roosters.com.au/news/2016/09/05/roosters-2016-season-review/</ref>\n\nThe Roosters finished 2nd at the end of the 2017 season and defeated Brisbane in week one of the finals earning the week off.  Sydney's opponents in the Preliminary Final were North Queensland who had finished in 8th position on the table and produced upset victories over Cronulla and Parramatta.  In a game that the Roosters were expected to win, the Cowboys surprised everyone winning the match 29\u201316.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/08/16/sydney-roosters-boyd-cordner-wont-let-the-scars-of-past-finals-series-hurt-this-year/</ref><ref>https://www.roosters.com.au/news/2017/09/25/roosters-2017--season-review/</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the Sydney Roosters finished in first place during the regular season, claiming their 20th Minor Premiership. They beat [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks|Cronulla-Sutherland]] 21\u201312 in week one of the finals, earning the week off.\n\nThey then broke their preliminary final hoodoo, beating rivals [[South Sydney Rabbitohs|South Sydney]] 12\u20134 in what was the last sports match ever played at the [[Sydney Football Stadium]]. They managed to keep Souths tryless, and the crowd was the highest ever recorded in a sporting match at the [[Sydney Football Stadium]] with 44,380 people attending the match. They played Melbourne in the [[2018 NRL Grand Final]], and won 21\u20136 to claim their 14th premiership.\n\nThe Roosters started the [[2019 NRL season]] with a round 1 loss against rivals Souths at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].  The club then went on an eight game winning run and defeated Melbourne 21\u201320 in the grand final rematch which was played at [[AAMI Park]] in the process.  The Roosters also scored impressive victories over Brisbane defeating them 36\u20134 and Wests 42\u201312 which were both played at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/mitchell-s-boot-floors-storm-in-golden-point-classic-20190419-p51fqf.html/|title=Mitchell's boot floors Storm in golden-point classic|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-05-04/nrl-raiders-panthers-sea-eagles-bulldogs-roosters-wests-tigers/11062620/|title=Roosters thrash Tigers 42\u201312, Raiders beat Panthers 30\u201312, Sea Eagles defeat Bulldogs 18\u201310|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n\nDuring the midway point of the [[2019 NRL season]], the club suffered a drop in form during the [[2019 State of Origin series]] period before ending the season winning 7 of their last 8 matches to finish 2nd behind minor premiers Melbourne.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/08/04/brett-morris-racks-up-try-150-as-roosters-outclass-titans/|title=Horror show for Holbrook as Roosters run riot|website=NRL}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nrl/story/_/id/27226078/nrl-sydney-roosters-thrash-newcastle-knights-lose-jake-friend/|title=Sydney Roosters thrash Newcastle Knights, lose Jake Friend|publisher=ESPN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/mitchell-stars-as-roosters-thump-hapless-warriors-20190818-p52ia7.html/|title=Mitchell stars as Roosters thump hapless Warriors|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\nThe club would then go on to defeat rivals [[South Sydney Rabbitohs|South Sydney]] and Melbourne to reach the [[2019 NRL Grand Final]].  In the grand final, the club would go on to win their second consecutive premiership after a hard fought victory against Canberra at [[ANZ Stadium]].  It was the first time that a team had won consecutive premierships in a unified competition since Brisbane achieved the feat in the 1992 and 1993 seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-grand-final-player-ratings-roosters-and-raiders-hits-and-misses-20191006-p52y53.html/|title=NRL grand final player ratings: Roosters and Raiders hits and misses|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/49950757/|title=Sydney Roosters beat Canberra Raiders to win NRL Grand Final|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Emblem==\nEastern Suburbs did not traditionally sport a crest on their jerseys in the first half of the 20th century.<ref>Collis and Whiticker, pp. 14\u201327.</ref> Other clubs occasionally sported simple designs on their strip; however, this was not seen consistently on all jerseys until the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name=cw23/> In 1967, the club introduced its first logo, displaying the mantra \"Easts to Win\",<!-- SOURCE IN NEXT FACT --> following a winless season.<ref name=cw23/> The crest also incorporated a [[rooster]] or cockerel in the design; one source suggested that this choice of mascot followed after the Roosters' jersey design was inspired by the [[France national rugby league team|French national team's]] jersey.<ref name=cw24/><ref>{{cite web|last=Fagan |first=Sean |url=http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/100years/news.php?article_id=41  |title=Origin of the Rooster and club colours |publisher=Sydney Roosters |date=31 July 2006 |accessdate=10 August 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070921044707/http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/100years/news.php?article_id=41 |archivedate = 21 September 2007}}</ref> Given that the French team's mascot was affectionately known to supporters as ''le coq'', \"the rooster\", connections have been made as to the choosing of a rooster for Eastern Suburbs' mascot.<ref name=cw24/>\n\nIn 1978, the mantra was replaced with the team's name, \"Eastern Suburbs\".<ref name=cw27/> This name was kept until 1994,<ref name=cw27/> when the club changed its team name to the \"Sydney City Roosters\" for the start of the 1995 season to appeal to the club's widening fan base.<ref name=cw27/> In 2000, the club shortened its name to the \"Sydney Roosters\".<ref name=cw27/>\n\nAlthough marketing names have changed, the Roosters are still registered with the National Rugby League competition as the Eastern Suburbs District Rugby League Football Club, the entity holding the NRL licence.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bryce |first=Shannon |url=http://www.rleague.com/db/club/sydney_roosters/history.php |title=Sydney Roosters History |publisher=The World of Rugby League |access-date=10 July 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001421/http://www.rleague.com/db/club/sydney_roosters/history.php |archive-date=1 October 2007 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Colours==\nRed, white and blue have been the colours of every jersey design in the club's history;<ref>{{cite web|last=Fagan |first=Sean |url=http://www.rl1908.com/clubcomps/origins.htm |title=Club Histories \u2013 New Speculations |publisher=Rl1908.com |access-date=4 November 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061021080342/http://www.rl1908.com/clubcomps/origins.htm |archive-date=21 October 2006  }}</ref> however, the jersey design has undergone several alterations. The red, white and blue colour scheme has traditionally been the colour combination of sporting teams representing Sydney's Eastern Suburbs. Eastern Suburbs Rugby League club adopted these colours in 1908, with its predecessor Rugby Union club, also known as Eastern Suburbs in the Sydney club Rugby Union, having played in the tricolours. The jersey worn in the first premiership season consisted of several hoops; red stripes dominated over consecutive smaller white and blue stripes. Although the width and the order of these stripes have changed, the basic design has always been maintained.\n\nDuring World War II, the design of the jersey was modified because the dye used to colour jerseys was needed for the war effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=12246|title=War Jersey In-Store NOW|accessdate=14 April 2009|publisher=Sydney Roosters|date=31 March 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314064903/http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=12246|archivedate=14 March 2012}}</ref> This saw Eastern Suburbs playing in different colours and an altered design. Instead of using the traditional hoops, the side used a sky-blue based jersey and a red and white V-strip around the collar. This is the only noted time in the club's history where the traditional deep blue, red and white combination was absent from the jersey. After the war, the V-strip design reverted to the original blue that had been present in the original jerseys, and the single red and white stripes around the shirt's chest were incorporated with a single white stripe surrounded by a red stripe on either side. This jersey appeared in the 1950s and remains the team's base design.<ref name=cw23/>\n\nFacing design clashes with other teams in the 1990s, the club adopted a jersey with a similar design to what became known as the \"away jersey\", replacing the blue backing with white, and the outer red stripe with blue. As the club entered the new century, the team began to wear a \"foundation jersey\". Although the design differs slightly from the jersey worn in the inaugural 1908 season, it did feature the traditional horizontal striped-design. This jersey is normally worn when the Sydney Roosters face traditional rivals, such as the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]], or on special occasions such as [[Anzac Day]] when the team meets the [[St George Illawarra Dragons]], the product of a team partly formed by the [[St. George Dragons]].\n\n==Rivals==\n\nMain: [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]], [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]], [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]].\n\nMinor: [[Penrith Panthers]], [[Manly Warringah Sea Eagles]], [[Melbourne Storm]], [[Brisbane Broncos]], [[Canberra Raiders]], [[New Zealand Warriors]].\n\n==Geographic area==\nThe Sydney Roosters, namely the Eastern Suburbs District Rugby League Football Club was formed, under its articles of association with the NSWRL, to represent the geographic areas in Sydney covering the Waverley, Randwick, Woollahra, Paddington, Darlinghurst and Vaucluse local government municipalities, as well as the eastern parts of the Sydney CBD. Despite some junior Rugby League boundaries being redrawn over the 107-year history of the code in Australia, these articles of association remain unchanged. As such, the Roosters represent a small area of Sydney.  The Roosters home turf is also home to a large number of supporters of rival codes and thus is the most competitive sporting market in Australia, with the Roosters flying the flag for Rugby League in Sydney's east.\n\n==Stadium==\nMost sources suggest that the [[Sydney Showground (Moore Park)|Royal Agricultural Ground]] was often used as a home venue between 1908 and 1910, before the club hosted matches at the [[Sydney Sports Ground]] from 1911 onwards.<ref name=cw16/><ref>[http://www.angelfire.com/nb/coop/bryce/records.html The Australian Rugby League records] ''Co-op'' Retrieved 6 October 2006.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/100years/timeline_iframe.php  |title=Timeline |publisher=Sydney Roosters |accessdate=6 October 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070501131823/http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/100years/timeline_iframe.php |archivedate = 1 May 2007}}</ref> It was here that the team played all of their home games up until 1986, when the ground was demolished with the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]] No. 2 to make way for Sydney's main rectangular field, the [[Sydney Football Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.cricinfo.com/australia/content/ground/56546.html |title=Sydney Cricket Ground No. 2 |publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=6 October 2006}}</ref> In 1987, games were moved away to the [[Newtown Jets]]' home ground, [[Henson Park]], temporarily to await the completion of the Sydney Football Stadium. The team capitalised on this move, finishing second in the regular season. It was the only time between 1983 and 1995 that the side reached the finals.<ref name=\"season\" />\n\n[[File:Sydney Sports Ground 1937.jpg|thumb|General view of the former [[Sydney Sports Ground]], [[Moore Park, New South Wales|Moore Park]], as it appeared in 1937.]]\n\nIn 1988, the club moved to the newly built Sydney Football Stadium on the site of the old Sydney Sports Ground,<ref name=cw26/> opening the season with a 24\u201314 defeat at the hands of the St George Dragons in front of 19,295 spectators on a wet night on 4 March 1988.<ref name=AllGames>{{cite web|title=Rugby League Tables / All Games / Sydney Roosters|url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/games/easts.html|author=Jeffs, Paul|publisher=Rugby League Tables & Statistics|access-date=13 April 2009|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070819174544/http://stats.rleague.com/rl/games/easts.html |archive-date = 19 August 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the Sydney Football Stadium, the Roosters have a 59% win record from 256 games with a 58% and 55% win record at their old grounds the Sydney Sports Ground and the Sydney Cricket Ground respectively.<ref>{{cite web|access-date=13 April 2009|title=Rugby League Tables / Win-Loss Record / Venues / Sydney Roosters|url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/easts/easts_vn.html|publisher=Rugby League Tables & Statistics|author=Jeffs, Paul|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419173600/http://stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/easts/easts_vn.html|archive-date=19 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aussie Stadium.jpg|thumb|The [[Sydney Football Stadium]] as it appears while hosting a [[National Rugby League]] finals match.]]\n\nThe Roosters played their last game at the Sydney Football Stadium on 22 September 2018 in front of a ground record crowd (44,380). In 2019 the Sydney Roosters home became the Sydney Cricket Ground whilst the [[Sydney Football Stadium (2022)]] is built.<ref>https://www.roosters.com.au/news/2019/03/25/scg-trust-roosters-agree-to-25-year-partnership/</ref>\n\n==Supporters==\nWhilst the Roosters have supporters all around the world, its traditional fan base is in Sydney, which is most concentrated in its homeland in the affluent eastern suburbs.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/fans/roostersaustraliawide.php  |title=Roosters Australia Wide |publisher=Sydney Roosters |accessdate=9 August 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060709080241/http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/fans/roostersaustraliawide.php |archivedate = 9 July 2006}}</ref> The club has an internet message board for supporters, \"The Wall\", which has been the official forum since 1999. The club has announced that \"The Wall\" will be closing as of late January 2012. \"The Chookpen\" is an unofficial site.<!--is this bit about forums necessary?-->\n\nIn 2013 the club tallied the fourth-highest home attendance of all National Rugby League clubs (behind the [[Brisbane Broncos]]) with an average of 19,368 spectators at the [[Sydney Football Stadium]].<ref name=\"attendance\">{{cite web | url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/crowds/2013.html | title=Rugby League Tables / 2013 Attendances | publisher=Rugby League Tables & Statistics | access-date=9 November 2013 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109052306/http://stats.rleague.com/rl/crowds/2013.html | archive-date=9 November 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt the club's home ground, the Sydney Football Stadium, the supporters congregate in distinct sections. The \"Chook Pen\", a designated area in Bay 35,<ref>{{cite news|last=Constantinou|first=Menios|title=It's Rooster season|work=Wentworth Courier|date=24 February 2010|page=3}}</ref> is the preferred location for the most animated fans.<ref>{{cite news|last=Huxley|first=John|title=Geez, don't you just glove those Roosters?|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=26 August 2000|page=1}}</ref> Members of the Sydney Cricket and Sports Ground Trust are seated in the Members Pavilion,<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership: SCG Membership|publisher=Sydney Cricket and Sports Ground Trust|url=http://www.sydneycricketground.com.au/membership/|accessdate=16 September 2017}}</ref> and season ticket holders are located in Bays 12\u201314.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://membership.roosters.com.au/use-your-membership|title=How to use your Roosters Membership|publisher=Sydney Roosters|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the Roosters had over 16,000 paying members, in addition to the 41,980 members of the Roosters' Leagues Club, which is the major benefactor of the football club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eastsgroup.com.au/assets/images/Easts_Leagues_Annual_Report_2017.pdf|title=Easts Leagues Club Annual Report|publisher=Sydney Roosters|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> The [[Eastern Suburbs Leagues Club|Easts Leagues Club]] and the Sydney Roosters \"operate as one entity\" known as the Easts Group.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Eastern Suburbs Leagues Club|title=2013 Annual Report|url=http://www.eastleaguesclub.com.au/default.aspx?id=281|access-date=30 January 2013|format=PDF|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130410093447/http://www.eastleaguesclub.com.au/default.aspx?id=281|archive-date=10 April 2013}}</ref> Under this arrangement, the Eastern Suburbs District Rugby League Football Club is the 'parent company' of the Easts Group. The Football Club delegates, however, overarching responsibility for both football and leagues club operations to a single general manager who oversees the whole group's performance. The leagues club group provides financial support to the football club, only where necessary, as in recent years the football club's sponsorships and TV revenues are generally covering most Rugby League expenditures.\n\n===Notable supporters===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* [[Doug Bollinger]]<br/><small>cricketer</small><ref name=\"Weidler\">{{cite news|first=Danny|last=Weidler|authorlink=Danny Weidler|title=Last word: Stuart's cock-a-hoop|newspaper=The Sun-Herald|date=9 November 2003}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Bouris]]<br/><small>businessman</small><ref>{{cite news|first=Roy|last=Masters|title=Origin II presents the praised, the persecuted, the steward and the sledgehammer|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=smh&kw=%22roosters+supporter%22&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SMH030625PPDC53719SJ|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=5 June 2003|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Guillaume Brahimi]]<br/><small>chef</small><ref>{{cite news|first=Christine|last=Lacy|title=Telstra now on to its second pick|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=smh&Page=1&docID=SMH050601SQ71D3KL4OA|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=1 June 2005|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Simon Burke]]<br/><small>actor</small><ref>{{cite news|first=Rachel|last=Browne|title=My Week: Simon Burke, actor|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=smh&kw=%22roosters+supporter%22&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SHD050724BJ19B5A13N9|newspaper=The Sun-Herald|date=24 July 2005|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Scott Cam]]<br/><small>television host</small><ref>{{cite news|first=Roy|last=Masters|title=Origin II presents the praised, the persecuted, the steward and the sledgehammer|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page1&sy=smh&kw=%22roosters+supporter%22&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SMH030625PPDC53719SJ|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=5 June 2003|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Carr]]<br/><small>39th [[Premier of New South Wales]]</small><ref>{{cite news|first=Roy|last=Masters|title=Clubs are overdoing this 'them' and 'us' approach|u