<small>professional golfer</small><ref name=\"Weidler\">{{cite news|first=Danny|last=Weidler|authorlink=Danny Weidler|title=Last word: Stuart's cock-a-hoop|newspaper=The Sun-Herald|date=9 November 2003}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Sheehan (journalist)|Paul Sheehan]]<br/><small>columnist</small><ref>{{cite news|first=Paul|last=Sheehan|authorlink=Paul Sheehan (journalist)|title=Forget history ... the real winner will not be rugby league|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=smh&kw=%22roosters+fan%22&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=news000823_0783_5200|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=23 August 2000|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Smith (cricketer)|Steve Smith]]<br/><small>former captain of the [[Australia national cricket team|Australia cricket team]]</small><ref name=\"Smith and Warner\">{{cite news|first=Ben|last=Horne|title=Steve Smith and David Warner flying NRL flag in the Australian cricket team|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/roosters/steve-smith-and-david-warner-flying-nrl-flag-in-the-australian-cricket-team/news-story/5ff721555c2656b7fc17d9a25cc202e5|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=News Corp Australia|date=4 September 2015|accessdate=13 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Malcolm Turnbull]]<br/><small>29th [[Prime Minister of Australia]]</small><ref>{{cite news|first=Simon|last=King|title=Malcolm Turnbull is a rugby union man but in league with the voters|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/malcolm-turnbull-is-a-rugby-union-man-but-in-league-with-the-voters/news-story/e4ee486e23021a10d5756247fa82512e|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|publisher=[[News Corp Australia]]|date=16 September 2015|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Kate Waterhouse]]<br/><small>media personality</small><ref name=\"Keller, McNaught and Waterhouse\"/>\n* [[David Warner (cricketer)|David Warner]]<br/><small>former vice captain of the Australia cricket team</small><ref name=\"Smith and Warner\"/>\n* [[Tim Webster]]<br/><small>radio and television personality</small><ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew|last=Webster|title=NRL finals 2015: Sydney Roosters wary of Canterbury Bulldogs' tackling style|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/nrl-finals-2015-sydney-roosters-wary-of-canterbury-bulldogs-tackling-style-20150917-gjopyo..html|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=17 September 2015|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Gus Worland]]<br/><small>Media personality</small>\n}}\n\n==Statistics and records==\n{{Main|List of Sydney Roosters records}}\n[[Anthony Minichiello]] holds the record for the most first grade games (302),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/Luke_Ricketson/summary.html|title=Luke Ricketson \u2013 Summary|publisher=Rugby League Project|accessdate=13 April 2009|author1=Dollin, Shaun  |author2=Ferguson, Andrew |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> having surpassed [[Luke Ricketson]]'s tally of 301 matches<!--SOURCE IS IN THE NEXT REF --> in round 3 of the finals in 2014.<ref name=cw27/> Former team captain [[Craig Fitzgibbon]] holds the club record for scoring the most points, tallying 1,376 over his 210 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/Craig_Fitzgibbon/summary.html|title=Craig Fitzgibbon -Summary|publisher=Rugby League Project|accessdate=13 April 2009|author1=Dollin, Shaun  |author2=Ferguson, Andrew |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/easts/easts_sc.html|title=Rugby League Tables / Sydney Roosters Scorers|author=Jeffs, Paul|publisher=Rugby League Tables & Statistics|access-date=13 April 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090324072506/http://stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/easts/easts_sc.html|archive-date=24 March 2009}}</ref> Fitzgibbon also broke the all-time point scoring record for a forward in the later rounds of 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Sport/Fitzgibbon-now-highestscoring-forward/2006/08/12/1154803146140.html|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=13 April 2009|title=Fitzgibbon now highest-scoring forward|date=12 August 2006}}</ref> [[Dave Brown (rugby league, born 1913)|Dave Brown's]] tally of 45 points (five tries and 15 goals) in a single match against [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Canterbury]] in 1935 remains a competition record after more than seven decades.<ref name=cw29/> [[Ivan Cleary]] scored 284 points in 1998,<ref name=cw29/> which at the time was an all-time points scoring record in a season.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2003/09/21/950336.htm | title=Bulldogs blow Storm away | work=ABC | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation | date=21 September 2003 | accessdate=18 April 2009 | author=Zander, Joel}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill Mullins]], father of 2002 premiership player [[Brett Mullins|Brett]], scored 104 tries in his 11-year, 190-game career with Eastern Suburbs between 1968 and 1978,<ref name=cw29/> meaning that on average, he scored at least one try every two games.<!-- SOURCE: Simple Maths 104 into 190 means a try every 0.55 a match or more than twice a game --> [[Anthony Minichiello]] became the highest try scorer in the Roosters history when he scored his 105th try against the [[Newcastle Knights|Newcastle]] at [[Newcastle International Sports Centre|Ausgrid Stadium]] in June 2011. [[Anthony Minichiello|'Mini']] finally retired after the 2014 season, and ended his career with 139 tries. He is also the first fullback in 70 years to win the Grand Final (2013), whilst captaining the Club. [[Rod O'Loan]] scored seven tries in a single match against [[Sydney University rugby league team|Sydney University]] in 1935,<ref name=cw29/> and Dave Brown's 38 tries in 15 games in the same year remains a competition record.<ref name=cw29/>\n\nIn 1975, the Eastern Suburbs Roosters set an unparalleled 19-match winning streak on their way to their 11th premiership.<ref name=cw25/> In a 1935 match against Canterbury, Dave Brown scored 45 points, the highest score and victory margin for the club (the 87\u20137 scoreline is equivalent to 106\u20138 under the contemporary scoring system).<ref name=cw29/> The winning margin is the second largest overall, behind [[St. George Dragons|St. George's]] 91\u20136 win over Canterbury a week earlier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/all/overall_gr.html |title=Rugby League Tables / Game Records / All Teams |access-date=13 April 2009 |author=Jeffs, Paul |publisher=Rugby League Tables & Statistics |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717162122/http://stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/all/overall_gr.html |archive-date=17 July 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe club's record attendance for a regular season game at its home ground\u2014the Sydney Football Stadium\u2014stands at 40,864, achieved in a match on [[ANZAC Day]] against the [[St George Illawarra Dragons]] in 2017.<ref name=AllGames/> The club's record attendance for a regular season game at the SCG stands at 50,130 on 4 May 1974 against the Manly Sea Eagles<ref name=AllGames/>\n \nThe 2000 grand final between the Sydney Roosters and the [[Brisbane Broncos]] attracted 94,277 spectators to the Olympic Stadium.<ref name=AllGames/>\n\n==Squads==\n{{See also|List of Sydney Roosters players}}\n\n===Current squad===\n{{Sydney Roosters Current Squad}}\n\n===Team of the Century===\nIn 2000, the Sydney Roosters named their \"Team of the Century\", which included players from 1908 to 2000. The official team is listed below along with their Sydney Roosters [[cap (sport)|cap]] number.<ref name=\"Player List\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/100years/player_list.php  |title=Player List |publisher=Sydney Roosters |accessdate=4 November 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080103124027/http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/100years/player_list.php |archivedate = 3 January 2008}}</ref>\n{{Rls\n|squadname=Team of the Century\n|BC1=#000080\n|FC1=white\n|BC2=red\n|FC2=white\n|source=[https://web.archive.org/web/20080103124027/http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/100years/player_list.php Player List] (archived)\n|date= 22 October 2011\n|list1a={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=639 | pos=FB | name=[[Russell Fairfax]]}}\n|list1b={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=587 | pos=WG | name=[[Bill Mullins]]}}\n|list1c={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=&nbsp;18 | pos=CE | name=[[Dally Messenger]]}}\n|list1d={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=202 | pos=CE | name=[[Dave Brown (rugby league, born 1913)|David Brown]]}}\n|list1e={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=315 | pos=WG | name=[[Lionel Cooper (rugby league)|Lionel Cooper]]}}\n|list1f={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=948 | pos=FE | name=[[Brad Fittler]]}}\n|list1g={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=210 | pos=HB | name=[[Viv Thicknesse]]}}\n|list1h={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=190 | pos=PR | name=[[Ray Stehr]]}}\n|list1i={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=&nbsp;10 | pos=HK | name=[[Sandy Pearce]]}}\n|list1j={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=615 | pos=PR | name=[[Arthur Beetson]]}}\n|list1k={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=625 | pos=SR | name=[[Ron Coote]]}}\n|list1l={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=193 | pos=SR | name=[[Joe Pearce]]}}\n|list1m={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=234 | pos=LK | name=[[Andy Norval]]}}\n|list2a={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=674 | name=[[Kevin Hastings]]}}\n|list2b={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=232 | name=[[Jack Beaton]]}}\n|list2c={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=&nbsp;66 | name=[[Jack Watkins]]}}\n|list2d={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=570 | name=[[Barry Reilly]]}}\n|coach=[[Jack Gibson (rugby league)|Jack Gibson]]\n}}\n\n===The Centurions===\nIn 2007, the Sydney Roosters announced \"The Centurions\", a team consisting of those regarded as the greatest players to have played 100 or more games for the club between 1908 and 2007. The team was selected by Ray Chesterton, Ian Heads, David Middleton and Alan Clarkson and was unveiled at the centenary season launch at the Michael Algeri Pavilion on 10 March 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/default.aspx?s=centurions|title=Centurions|access-date=13 April 2009|publisher=Sydney Roosters|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413055505/http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/default.aspx?s=centurions|archive-date=13 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,21353621-5001023,00.html|title=Twin signing boost for Roosters|accessdate=13 April 2009|date=10 March 2007|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|first=Steve|last=Mascourd}}</ref>\n{{Rls\n|squadname=The Centurions\n|BC1=#000080\n|FC1=white\n|BC2=red\n|FC2=white\n|source=[https://web.archive.org/web/20090413055505/http://www.sydneyroosters.com.au/default.aspx?s=centurions Centurions]\n|date= 22 October 2011\n|list1a={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=994 | pos=FB | name=[[Anthony Minichiello]]}}\n|list1b={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=587 | pos=WG | name=[[Bill Mullins]]}}\n|list1c={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=608 | pos=CE | name=[[Mark Harris (rugby league)|Mark Harris]]}}\n|list1d={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=595 | pos=CE | name=[[John Brass]]}}\n|list1e={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=650 | pos=WG | name=[[Ian Schubert]]}}\n|list1f={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=948 | pos=FE | name=[[Brad Fittler]]}}\n|list1g={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=674 | pos=HB | name=[[Kevin Hastings]]}}\n|list1h={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=190 | pos=PR | name=[[Ray Stehr]]}}\n|list1i={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=&nbsp;10 | pos=HK | name=[[Sandy Pearce]]}}\n|list1j={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=615 | pos=PR | name=[[Arthur Beetson]]|captain=y}}\n|list1k={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=625 | pos=SR | name=[[Ron Coote]]}}\n|list1l={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=193 | pos=SR | name=[[Joe Pearce]]}}\n|list1m={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=234 | pos=LK | name=[[Andy Norval]]}}\n|list2a={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=989 | pos=SR | name=[[Craig Fitzgibbon]]}}\n|list2b={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=206 | name=[[Ernie Norman]]}}\n|list2c={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=884 | pos=LK | name=[[Luke Ricketson]]}}\n|list2d={{Rls player | nat=AUS | no=570 | name=[[Barry Reilly]]}}\n|coach=[[Jack Gibson (rugby league)|Jack Gibson]]\n}}\n\n==Honours==\n{{Main|List of Sydney Roosters honours}}\n\n===Titles===\n'''Premierships \u2013 15'''<br/>1911, 1912, 1913, 1923, 1935, 1936, 1937, 1940, 1945, 1974, 1975, 2002, 2013, 2018, 2019\n\n'''Runners-up \u2013 15'''<br/>1908, 1919, 1921, 1928, 1931, 1934, 1938, 1941, 1960, 1972, 1980, 2000, 2003, 2004, 2010\n\n'''Minor Premierships \u2013 20'''<br/>1912, 1913, 1923, 1931, 1934, 1935, 1936, 1937, 1940, 1941, 1945, 1974, 1975, 1980, 1981, 2004, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2018\n\n'''World Club Challenge \u2013 5'''<br/>1976, 2003, 2014, 2019, 2020\n\n'''Amco Cup \u2013 2'''<br/>{{space|5}}1975, 1978\n\n'''City Cup \u2013 3'''<br/>{{space|5}}1914, 1915, 1916\n\n'''Auckland Nines \u2013 1'''<br/>{{space|5}}2017\n\n'''World Sevens \u2013 1'''<br/>{{space|5}}1993\n\n===Youth/Pre-season Titles===\n'''Club Championship \u2013 12'''<br/>{{space|5}}1930, 1931, 1934, 1935, 1936, 1937, 1945, 1970, 1974, 1975, 2004, 2006\n\n'''Second Grade \u2013 9'''<br/>{{space|5}}1908, 1909, 1910, 1911, 1935, 1937, 1949, 1986, 2004\n\n'''Third Grade/Under 23 \u2013 11'''<br/>{{space|5}}1914, 1917, 1924, 1929, 1930, 1931, 1932, 1941, 1947, 1970, 1976\n\n'''National Youth Competition \u2013 1'''<br/>{{space|5}}2016\n\n'''Jersey Flegg Cup \u2013 3'''<br/>{{space|5}}1995, 2002, 2004\n\n'''Presidents Cup \u2013 16'''<br/>{{space|5}}1910, 1911, 1913, 1915, 1920, 1922, 1923, 1924, 1927, 1938, 1948, 1949, 1955, 1978, 1987, 1993\n\n'''S. G. Ball Cup \u2013 4'''<br/>{{space|5}}1997, 2008, 2010, 2014\n\n'''Pre-Season Cup \u2013 4'''<br/>{{space|5}}1974, 1977, 1979, 1981\n\n==NRL Women's team==\nOn 27 March 2018, the Sydney Roosters applied for, and won, a license to participate in the inaugural [[2018 NRL Women's season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/03/27/geographic-location-the-focus-as-nrl-womens-teams-announced/|title=Geographic location the focus as NRL women's teams announced|publisher=NRL.com|first=Alicia|last=Newton|date=27 March 2018|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref> [[Adam Hartigan]] was named as the coach of the women's side.\n\nIn June 2018, the club used up the maximum of fifteen marquee signings ahead of the inaugural season which will commence in September, including [[Karina Brown]], [[Isabelle Kelly]] and [[Ruan Sims]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roosters.com.au/news/2018/06/17/roosters-announce-nrlw-marquee-signings/|title=Roosters announce NRLW marquee signings|publisher=Sydney Roosters|date=17 June 2018|accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe club finished runners-up in the inaugural [[NRL Women's Premiership]], losing to the [[Brisbane Broncos (NRLW)|Brisbane Broncos]] by 34\u201312 in the [[2018 NRL Women's Premiership Grand Final]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/09/30/brisbane-broncos-smash-roosters-to-win-inaugural-holden-womens-premiership/|title=Broncos smash Roosters to win inaugural NRLW|publisher=NRL.com|first=Alicia|last=Newton|date=30 September 2018|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Current squad ===\n{{Sydney Roosters women's squad}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add references to this article, please see http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cite/Cite.php -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n<!-- *{{cite web\n   |title=Rugby League Tables and Statistics\n   |work=The World of Rugby League\n   |url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/rl_index.html\n   |accessdate=8 October 2006}}\n*{{cite web\n   |title=Hall of Fame\n   |publisher=Australian Rugby League\n   |url=http://www.australianrugbyleague.com.au/index.cgi?sID=10\n   |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061005094418/http://www.australianrugbyleague.com.au/index.cgi?sID=10\n   |archivedate=5 October 2006\n|accessdate=8 October 2006}} -->\n* {{Cite 