{"title_page": "National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control", "text_new": "The U.S. '''National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control''' was a [[Presidential Commission (United States)|Presidential Commission]] appointed by President [[Richard Nixon]] in June 1971. It submitted its final report, ''[[America Burning]]'', in July 1973.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Fire Research and Safety Act of 1968]] provided a [[Mandate (politics)|mandate]] for a Presidential Commission to be established for research into the hazards of death, injury, and [[property damage]] caused by fire. [[Act of Congress|Public Law]] 90-259 authorized a twenty-member commission to conduct a two-year study aiming to determine effective measures for reducing the destructive effects of fire.\n\n==Activities==\nDuring 1972, the [[Presidential Task Force]] conducted regional hearings across the United States surveying communities with regards to [[Flammability|flammable]] incidences.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=3361 |title=Richard Nixon: \"Statement on Receiving the First Report of the National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control.,\" March 31, 1972 |author1=Peters, Gerhard |author2=Woolley, John T |publisher = University of California - Santa Barbara |work= The American Presidency Project}}</ref> The Presidential Commission concluded their study on May 4, 1973, submitting a report to President Nixon entitled ''America Burning: The Report of The National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usfa.fema.gov/downloads/pdf/publications/fa-264.pdf |title=America Burning : The Report of The National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control |date=May 4, 1973 |website=U.S. Fire Administration |publisher=Federal Emergency Management Agency |pages=192 |oclc=23601256}}</ref> On July 12, 1973, President Nixon released a presidential statement commending the National Commission on their [[analysis]] and findings related to [[fire safety]] and the fire loss dilemma in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=3899 |title=Richard Nixon: \"Statement About the Final Report of the National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control,\" July 12, 1973 |author1=Peters, Gerhard |author2=Woolley, John T |publisher = University of California - Santa Barbara |work= The American Presidency Project}}</ref>\n\n==Commissioners==\nNixon appointed [[commissioner]]s for the National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control in June 1971.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! NCFPC Commissioner\n! Occupation\n! Affiliation\n|-\n|Richard E. Bland\n|{{unbulleted list|Commission Chairman|Professor of Engineering}}\n|[[Pennsylvania State University]]\n|-\n|W. Howard McClennan\n|{{unbulleted list|Commission Vice Chairman|President}}\n|[[International Association of Fire Fighters]]\n|-\n|Howard Tipton\n|Executive Director\n|National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control\n|-\n|Ernst R.G. Eckert, Ph.D.\n|Professor of Mechanical Engineering  \n|[[University of Minnesota]]\n|-\n|Peter S. Hackes\n|Media Correspondent\n|[[NBC|National Broadcasting Company]]\n|-\n|John L. Jablonsky\n|Vice President\n|[[American Insurance Association]]\n|-\n|Ann Wight Phillips, M.D.\n|Burn Specialist\n|{{unbulleted list|[[Harvard Medical School]]|[[Massachusetts General Hospital]]}}\n|-\n|Dorothy Duke\n|Consultant\n|[[National Council of Negro Women]]\n|-\n|Albert Hole\n|Fire Marshal\n|[[California|State of California]]\n|-\n|Baron Whitaker\n|President\n|[[UL (safety organization)|Underwriter Laboratories]]\n|-\n|Percy Bugbee\n|Honorary Chairman\n|[[National Fire Protection Association]]\n|-\n|Roger Freeman Jr.\n|President\n|Allendale Mutual Insurance Co.\n|-\n|Tommy Arevalo\n|Lieutenant \n|[[El Paso, Texas]] Fire Department\n|-\n|Keith E. Klinger\n|Chief Emeritus\n|[[Los Angeles County Fire Department]]\n|-\n|Robert A. Hechtman, Ph.D.\n|President\n|R.A. Hechtman & Associates\n|-\n|Louis J. Ambrili\n|Director \n|Delaware State Fire School\n|-\n|William J. Young\n|Fire Chief\n|[[Newington, New Hampshire]] Fire Department\n|-\n|John F. Hurley\n|Fire Commissioner\n|City of [[Rochester, New York]]\n|-\n|John A. Proven\n|Director\n|[[Fire Equipment Manufacturers' Association]]\n|-\n|Frederick B. Dent\n|Presidential Cabinet Member\n|[[United States Secretary of Commerce|Secretary of Commerce]]\n|- \n|James T. Lynn\n|Presidential Cabinet Member\n|[[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|Secretary of Housing]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons|Firefighting}}\n\n[[Category:1968 in law]]\n[[Category:90th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:United States national commissions]]\n[[Category:Firefighting in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fire prevention]]\n\n\n{{Firefighting-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The U.S. '''National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control''' was a [[Presidential Commission (United States)|Presidential Commission]] appointed by President [[Richard Nixon]] in June 1971. It submitted its final report, ''[[America Burning]]'', in july54600992 1973.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Fire Research and Safety Act of 1968]] provided a [[Mandate (politics)|mandate]] for a Presidential Commission to be established for research into the hazards of death, injury, and [[property damage]] caused by fire. [[Act of Congress|Public Law]] 90-259 authorized a twenty-member commission to conduct a two-year study aiming to determine effective measures for reducing the destructive effects of fire.\n\n==Activities==\nDuring 1972, the [[Presidential Task Force]] conducted regional hearings across the United States surveying communities with regards to [[Flammability|flammable]] incidences.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=3361 |title=Richard Nixon: \"Statement on Receiving the First Report of the National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control.,\" March 31, 1972 |author1=Peters, Gerhard |author2=Woolley, John T |publisher = University of California - Santa Barbara |work= The American Presidency Project}}</ref> The Presidential Commission concluded their study on May 4, 1973, submitting a report to President Nixon entitled ''America Burning: The Report of The National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usfa.fema.gov/downloads/pdf/publications/fa-264.pdf |title=America Burning : The Report of The National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control |date=May 4, 1973 |website=U.S. Fire Administration |publisher=Federal Emergency Management Agency |pages=192 |oclc=23601256}}</ref> On July 12, 1973, President Nixon released a presidential statement commending the National Commission on their [[analysis]] and findings related to [[fire safety]] and the fire loss dilemma in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=3899 |title=Richard Nixon: \"Statement About the Final Report of the National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control,\" July 12, 1973 |author1=Peters, Gerhard |author2=Woolley, John T |publisher = University of California - Santa Barbara |work= The American Presidency Project}}</ref>\n\n==Commissioners==\nNixon appointed [[commissioner]]s for the National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control in June 1971.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! NCFPC Commissioner\n! Occupation\n! Affiliation\n|-\n|Richard E. Bland\n|{{unbulleted list|Commission Chairman|Professor of Engineering}}\n|[[Pennsylvania State University]]\n|-\n|W. Howard McClennan\n|{{unbulleted list|Commission Vice Chairman|President}}\n|[[International Association of Fire Fighters]]\n|-\n|Howard Tipton\n|Executive Director\n|National Commission on Fire Prevention and Control\n|-\n|Ernst R.G. Eckert, Ph.D.\n|Professor of Mechanical Engineering  \n|[[University of Minnesota]]\n|-\n|Peter S. Hackes\n|Media Correspondent\n|[[NBC|National Broadcasting Company]]\n|-\n|John L. Jablonsky\n|Vice President\n|[[American Insurance Association]]\n|-\n|Ann Wight Phillips, M.D.\n|Burn Specialist\n|{{unbulleted list|[[Harvard Medical School]]|[[Massachusetts General Hospital]]}}\n|-\n|Dorothy Duke\n|Consultant\n|[[National Council of Negro Women]]\n|-\n|Albert Hole\n|Fire Marshal\n|[[California|State of California]]\n|-\n|Baron Whitaker\n|President\n|[[UL (safety organization)|Underwriter Laboratories]]\n|-\n|Percy Bugbee\n|Honorary Chairman\n|[[National Fire Protection Association]]\n|-\n|Roger Freeman Jr.\n|President\n|Allendale Mutual Insurance Co.\n|-\n|Tommy Arevalo\n|Lieutenant \n|[[El Paso, Texas]] Fire Department\n|-\n|Keith E. Klinger\n|Chief Emeritus\n|[[Los Angeles County Fire Department]]\n|-\n|Robert A. Hechtman, Ph.D.\n|President\n|R.A. Hechtman & Associates\n|-\n|Louis J. Ambrili\n|Director \n|Delaware State Fire School\n|-\n|William J. Young\n|Fire Chief\n|[[Newington, New Hampshire]] Fire Department\n|-\n|John F. Hurley\n|Fire Commissioner\n|City of [[Rochester, New York]]\n|-\n|John A. Proven\n|Director\n|[[Fire Equipment Manufacturers' Association]]\n|-\n|Frederick B. Dent\n|Presidential Cabinet Member\n|[[United States Secretary of Commerce|Secretary of Commerce]]\n|- \n|James T. Lynn\n|Presidential Cabinet Member\n|[[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|Secretary of Housing]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons|Firefighting}}\n\n[[Category:1968 in law]]\n[[Category:90th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:United States national commissions]]\n[[Category:Firefighting in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fire prevention]]\n\n\n{{Firefighting-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Informationdude420", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Commission_on_Fire_Prevention_and_Control"}
{"title_page": "Discovery Ski Area", "text_new": "{{Infobox ski area\n| name           = Discovery Ski Area\n| logo           = <!--  Commented out because image was deleted: Discovery.PNG -->\n| picture        =\n| caption        =\n| location       = [[Granite County, Montana]]\n| nearest_city   = [[Philipsburg, Montana]]\n| pushpin_map    = Montana#United States\n| pushpin_relief = 1\n| coordinates    = {{coord|46|15|23|N|113|14|31|W|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_label_position = \n| map_caption    = Location in [[Montana]]\n| top_elevation  = {{convert|8158|ft|m}}\n| base_elevation = {{convert|6480|ft|m}}\n| skiable_area   = {{convert|2200|acre|km2}}\n| number_trails  = 67\n| longest_run    = {{convert|1.5|mi|km}}\n| liftsystem     = 5 triples, 2 doubles, 1 surface\n| snowfall       = 215 \"\n| external_link  = [http://www.skidiscovery.com/ Official website]\n|}}\n\n'''Discovery Ski Area''' is an alpine [[ski area]] in the state of [[Montana]], [[United States]]. Situated on Rumsey and Jubilee mountains, the area consists of four different faces and provides for beginner groomed runs to expert bowl skiing. Discovery offers 2200 acres of skiing with over 8000 feet of elevation at the Summit. The ski area is often open early in the season and is known to stay open late into the next year often extending lift operations until the month of April. Discovery is usually only open on weekends to begin the season, but days and hours will often expand through the winter season.\n\n==Location==\nDiscovery is located near the town of [[Philipsburg, Montana]], off [[Montana Highway 1]], and is situated along the Pintler Scenic Loop opposite of Georgetown Lake.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.skidiscovery.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Montana Ski areas navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Granite County, Montana]]\n[[Category:Ski areas and resorts in Montana]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Granite County, Montana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ski area\n| name           = Discovery Ski Area\n| logo           = <!--  Commented out because image was deleted: Discovery.PNG -->\n| picture        =\n| caption        =\n| location       = [[Granite County, Montana]]\n| nearest_city   = [[Philipsburg, Montana]]\n| pushpin_map    = Montana#United States\n| pushpin_relief = 1\n| coordinates    = {{coord|46|15|23|N|113|14|31|W|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_label_position = \n| map_caption    = Location in [[Montana]]\n| top_elevation  = {{convert|8158|ft|m}}\n| base_elevation = {{convert|6480|ft|m}}\n| skiable_area   = {{convert|2200|acre|km2}}\n| number_trails  = 67\n| longest_run    = {{convert|1.5|mi|km}}\n| liftsystem     = 5 triples, 2 doubles, 1 surface\n| snowfall       = 215 \"\n| external_link  = [http://www.skidiscovery.com/ Official website]\n|}}\n\n'''Discovery Ski Area''' is an alpine [[ski area]] in the state of [[Montana]], [[United States]]. Situated on Rumsey and Jubilee mountains, the area consists of four different faces and provides for beginner groomed runs to expert bowl skiing. Discovery offers 2200 acres of skiing with 8,158 feet of elevation at the Summit. The ski area is often open early in the season and is known to stay open late into the next year often extending lift operations until the month of April. Discovery is usually only open on weekends to begin the season, but days and hours will often expand through the winter season.\n\n==Location==\nDiscovery is located near the town of [[Philipsburg, Montana]], off [[Montana Highway 1]], and is situated along the Pintler Scenic Loop opposite of Georgetown Lake.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.skidiscovery.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Montana Ski areas navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Granite County, Montana]]\n[[Category:Ski areas and resorts in Montana]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Granite County, Montana]]\n", "name_user": "Crcut", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor Edits (minor changes)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discovery_Ski_Area"}
